cs.CR, cs.IT, cs.DC, cs.DS, cs.CC 

The paper deals with information-theoretic security protocols that can tolerate an arbitrary number of corrupt participants. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the category of Cryptography and Security (cs.CR). Additionally, the paper involves the use of private channels and broadcast channels, which are related to Information Theory (cs.IT) and Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC). The paper also presents protocols for veto, vote, anonymous bit transmission, collision detection, notification, and anonymous message transmission, which are related to Distributed Systems (cs.DS) and Computer Communication and Networks (cs.CC).
